Fellowes Smart Suites Laptop Riser (8020201)

The Fellowes Smart Suites Laptop Riser with USB Hub encourages separate keyboard use to ensure correct ergonomic posture. Supports up to a 17 laptop or a maximum weight of 13 lbs. Offers three height adjustments for personal comfort. Accessory tray holds personal electronics and other items. Triangular design is vented to aid cooling, includes 4 port 2.0 USB hub, and fits neatly into desk corner.

  • Supports laptops up to 17 or 13 lbs
  • Offers three height adjustments

Dan
5.0 out of 5 stars Functional and durable
Reviewed in the United States on September 29, 2019
Verified Purchase
I originally bought my first Fellowes laptop riser in October of 2015. It has lived through two moves across country and only now needs to be replaced and not due to any failure of the product itself but a careless act.

When on a desk it appropriately elevates the screen at an angle that keeps me from looking down constantly at the screen. It allows me to keep almost a perfect ninety degree view angle. Does the screen tilt forward slightly? Yes it does, but that is due to the restrictions on the ASUS 17" laptop with a limit on how far back the screen goes. The rubber spacers are solid when they sit on a desk surface, though they can come loose when the stand is picked up. Nothing to cry about since they just pop back in. The riser does not take as much space as the laptop itself and also allows the fans to breathe easier and suck up less dust.
The phone ledge is convenient and gets a decent amount of use. The stand itself saves me room on an already tight desk surface and allows me to utilize the space underneath the stand for ExtHHDs or even a Blu-ray burner. The only issue I had was with the USB rail that needed to be replaced after the second year.
I only felt compelled to leave a review after looking for a replacement and happily finding it was still available. I only advise other prospective buyers to not let their laptops be the reason for giving a perfectly functional laptop riser a bad review. I should note, if you haven't already looked at product photo you will need to utilize a wireless keyboard and mouse. While the keyboard is open I typically use it for notes or photos when I am writing.

JP
5.0 out of 5 stars Near Perfect...
Reviewed in the United States on July 13, 2012
Verified Purchase
Changing your setup from having your notebook setting flat on your desktop to being elevated by this product is AMAZING. I was skeptical about investing $40 in a product for this purpose but compared to other products, the price is not too much more. What I enjoy about this product is the USB hub. The hub can be used separate from the riser if you choose but works perfectly to keep the connections out of sight and out of mind going out the back of the riser.

I was apprehensive about the riser covering my mouse pad but with a separate wireless mouse and keyboard combo, I find I don't mind the mouse pad being covered. I have used the slot on the front to hold my phone but mostly now I use if for holding business cards or post-it notes.

This riser is very good about allowing your computer to breath and keeping it pretty steady. This unit including the 2 additional feet risers (which are included) with a 15.4 in screen notebook will raise the very bottom of your note screen approx. 9 inches up vs. lying flat on your desktop (your height will vary based on you notebook measurements).
At home I often like to switch from using my notebook at my desk, to lying in bed using it, to taking it into different rooms in the house. Taking your notebook out and putting it back in this riser is not difficult and rather easy.

I say the unit is 'near perfect' because it didn't lift my screen as much as I would have hoped it could have. I can't count this against the riser but your experience will depend on the initial height of your desk. As I mentioned earlier, to get an estimate, with a standard 15.4 inch notebook computer, the bottom of your screen will be raised just at 9 inches higher than if it were lying flat. Overall, this is a good quality product and worth the price.

Roxy_Paper_Scissors
4.0 out of 5 stars Product works as Described
Reviewed in the United States on July 14, 2013
Verified Purchase
The bad: I really do not know how this happened, because you usually get "the feet wouldn't go into" or "the feet wouldn't STAY in", but I got both problems in the same product. The feet didn't fit snugly into the main body, I had to pound them in, as the cut of the rubber didn't match 100% where it was supposed to fit into. On the other hand, the feet wouldn't STAY put together either. You have to pick the device up off the table (the rubber DOES grip quite well) to move it, and all three feet would come apart from each other and the riser.

The good: The cover in the front is useful to train you out of using a touch-pad, and it holds a 17.3 in, 9.5 lb laptop securely and steady. The USB hub was very nice, and the unit gets wires out of your way. It is very customizable with three levels of rise to be had, The rubber grips the tabletop superbly. In fact, the unit (base plus laptop) would tip over before it would slide across --2 cats that love to push any and everything off table and counter-tops, so this is excellent. Materials are okay, and the plastic piece was built well.

Bottom line: This wasn't quite what I was looking for, but it works for now. A few minor annoyances, but a decent price is always an acceptable compromise for me.

Pepere Audibert
3.0 out of 5 stars Despite shortcomings, solved a pretty serious problem
Reviewed in the United States on November 30, 2012
Verified Purchase
I bought this thing because I spend long hours on my computer, and at the end of the day, my upper back and neck were screaming in pain. This product elevates the screen to eye level, and I use it with an inexpensive Microsoft keyboard that works very well, and have indeed solved my back/neck pain problem. That's the good part, here's the rest of my opinion about it:
This comes with a USB hub. It looks like it should mount somewhere on the unit to help keep the wires out of the way -- but it doesn't fit anywhere. There's a useless slot on the back that seems like it was designed to pass wiring, but there's no way this hub fits into that slot.
Second, if you look at a picture of this thing, you'll see a big flap on the front There seems to be a pocket in that flap that might hold a disc, but who would want a disc overlapping a keyboard? It's just plain annoying and would have been so much more effective with just a low bracket to keep the laptop secure. That's a fully functional keyboard under there, which I sometimes want to use because it contains media and other useful keys -- but the dumb flap . . . The setup sheet included in the box was entirely useless -- I was entirely on my own figuring out how to add the feet to cushion and raise my computer. Fortunately it's not rocket science, but the packaging and instructions are as annoying as their design.
But I no longer have a sore neck at the end of the day . . . all's well that ends well.

R. Stevens
5.0 out of 5 stars Great riser - solid, attractive and practical
Reviewed in the United Kingdom on September 17, 2010
Verified Purchase
I got one of these for a 15" MacBook Pro and haven't regretted it. It looks good, the desktop footprint is small, I find the height spot on and the built in USB hub is very handy. It also feels very sturdy and stable, which is reassuring if your laptop is expensive.

It's lucky I find the height agreeable because it is hardly adjustable. You get two sets of rubber feet that each add about 1cm to the height of your screen. But the option of using the lowest adjustment doesn't appeal since it leaves the hard plastic of the riser itself in contact with your desk, with all the sliding and noisy possibilities that entails. So if, like me, you always keep at least one set of feet in place you're left with 1cm of height adjustment, which is hardly worth mentioning.

Other drawbacks include the fact that the Fellowes riser appears to have been designed with brick-like 80's laptops in mind, since the gap between the transparent front cover and the back section on which the laptop rests is 4cm deep! Don't forget that your laptop is open when on the riser, so this leaves a yawning gap (about 3cm in my case) that the laptop is free to move around in. This is probably the biggest complaint I have about this riser.

Other niggles? Well, though it is nice the have a supplied USB hub, it would have been better to have a powered hub that could support things like portable external hard drives. With the one supplied you should only hope to be able to plug in things like keyboards and mice before it overloads. But that is probably what it is there for, making unplugging your laptop more painless at the end of the day, but it does limit your options.

I'm also undecided about the front "pocket". Using a Mac (without a MagicMouse) I would like to have access to the touchpad while the machine is in the riser, but the pocket blocks this, somewhat unnecessarily. However, because it is there I have found myself chucking little odds and ends (like USB keys) into it, which is actually very practical. Worth losing the touchpad for? Quite possibly. There's also stowage space available under the riser, which is also handy.

All-in-all, despite some of the design issues, I'm very happy with my choice and heartily recommend this great looking stand.

Verified Purchase
This is an excellent product for making laptops more ergonomical! I can now say my laptop screen is at the right height for me. I need to point out that you will need a separate keyboard because although the laptop keyboard isn't covered it is quite uncomfortable to use it when it is in position. The trackpad will be covered and unusable, but I use a mouse anyway. My only criticism would be that the rubber feet don't like staying where they should do; they come apart very easily.
